ernism, in ways that were not only aesthetic but also political. Harkema critically re-examines the relationship between Unamuno and several Spanish writers associated with the so-called Generation of 1927 (known as at the time as “la joven literatura” or “the young literature”). By situating this period within the wider framework of European modernism, Spanish Modernism and the Poetics of Youth brings to light the central role that the early twentieth century’s re-imagining of adolescence and youth played in the development of literary modernism in Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aModernism (Literature)zSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpanish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aYouth in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751433440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487514334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487514334.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles